:"0800","0822":"0822","before 0822":"før 0822","0867":"0867","Dynefwr Castle, Llandeilo, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llandeilo, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Dynevor, Llandilo, Carmarthen, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"Abt 822–867":"circa 0822–0867","0822–0867":"0822–0867","0820–0893":"0820–0893","0867–0904":"0867–0904","0870–0918":"0870–0918","0800–Male":"0800–Overleden","0800–Female":"0800–Overleden","0820":"0820","0893":"0893","0918":"0918","0870":"0870","Abt 822":"circa 0822","867":"0867","0904":"0904","0800":"0800","0822":"0822","before 0822":"vóór 0822","0867":"0867","Dynefwr Castle, Llandeilo, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llandeilo, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Dynevor, Llandilo, Carmarthen, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 822–867":"about 0822–0867","0822–0867":"0822–0867","0820–0893":"0820–0893","0867–0904":"0867–0904","0870–0918":"0870–0918","0800–Male":"0800–Deceased","0800–Female":"0800–Deceased","0820":"0820","0893":"0893","0918":"0918","0870":"0870","Abt 822":"about 0822","867":"0867","0904":"0904","0800":"0800","0822":"0822","before 0822":"before 0822","0867":"0867","Dynefwr Castle, Llandeilo, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llandeilo, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Dynevor, Llandilo, Carmarthen, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ferch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferg","meanings":["1  ‘Sharp blade’.","2  ‘Wind’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Maud ferch Maredudd was born about 0822, in Wales, her father, Maredudd ap Gruffudd, was 24 and her mother, Mrs Maredudd ap Gruffudd, was 23. She married Hyfaidd ap Bleddri King of Dyfed in Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 0867, at the age of 46."},"et":{"Abt 822–867":"umbes 0822–0867","0822–0867":"0822–0867","0820–0893":"0820–0893","0867–0904":"0867–0904","0870–0918":"0870–0918","0800–Male":"0800–Surnud","0800–Female":"0800–Surnud","0820":"0820","0893":"0893","0918":"0918","0870":"0870","Abt 822":"umbes 0822","867":"0867","0904":"0904","0800":"0800","0822":"0822","before 0822":"enne 0822","0867":"0867","Dynefwr Castle, Llandeilo, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llandeilo, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Dynevor, Llandilo, Carmarthen, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 822–867":"noin 0822–0867","0822–0867":"0822–0867","0820–0893":"0820–0893","0867–0904":"0867–0904","0870–0918":"0870–0918","0800–Male":"0800–Kuollut","0800–Female":"0800–Kuollut","0820":"0820